[Malignant catarrhal fever (MCF) is a generalized, often fatal disease caused by a [number of] herpesviruses that infect a variety of ruminants. The clinical course of the disease in individual animals is very varied and it may be peracute, acute, chronic, or mild. In the acute form of the disease, the clinical signs are usually severe inflammation of the mucosae of the respiratory and alimentary tracts and conjunctivae, as well as eyes and skin. The lesions are accompanied by mucopurulent discharge.

MCF is caused by several herpesvirus strains: alcelaphine herpesvirus 1 of wildebeests, ovine herpesvirus 2 of domestic sheep, and caprine herpesvirus 2 and MCFV-WTD virus of goats. None of these viruses causes clinical disease in their natural hosts.

A map of the affected area can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/8OsL. - Mod.PMB

A photo of a wildebeest (_Connochaetes_ sp.) is at:
http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fb/Blue_Wildebeest,_Ngorongoro.jpg
-Mod.JW]
